g themes in the study of art, from Impressionism to Abstract Art. Barasch details the immense social changes in the creation, presentation, and reception of art which have set the history of art theory on a vertiginous new course: the decreased relevance of workshops and art schools; the replacement of the treatise by the critical review; and the interrelation of new modes of scientific inquiry with artistic theory and praxis. The consequent changes in the ways in which critics as well as artists conceptualized paintings and sculptures were radical, marked by an obsession with intense, immediate sensory experiences, psychological reflection on the effects of art, and a magnetic pull to the exotic and alien, making for the most exciting and fertile period in the history of art criticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAesthetics, Moderny18th century. 0aAesthetics, Moderny19th century. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081471272640uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814709054.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814709054423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814709054/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK